In[]:
# Investigate car_model release_date respect to fuel_type
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

sns.scatterplot(data=cars_df, x='release_date', y='fuel_type', hue='fuel_type', palette='Set1', s=100)

for line in range(0, cars_df.shape[0]):
    plt.text(
        cars_df.release_date[line],
        cars_df.fuel_type[line],
        cars_df.car_model[line],
        horizontalalignment='left',
        size='small',
        color='black',
        rotation=45
    )

plt.title('Car Release Dates by Fuel Type', y=1.05)
plt.xlabel('Release Date')
plt.ylabel('Fuel Type')

plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.legend(title='Fuel Type')
plt.show()
Take-3

  • As can be seen from the plot above, diesel model cars (1 Series, Sierra, 3 Series) are older models with an average release year of 2013.33.

  • On the other hand, gasoline models (Coupe, Model M, Tourer, Sedan Touring) and electric models (Model iY, Model i7, Model iX, Model i8) are comparably younger, with average release dates for gasoline at 2017.0 and electric at 2016.25.

  • These two types are very similar to each other in terms of release date.

  • As time passes, the average duration of interaction does not change over time for purchase and testing visit types.
  • One possible explanation for this phenomenon could be that these interaction types involve user-filled information (such as personal data, card information, etc.), which takes a similar amount of time across different periods.
  • On the other hand, we observe an increase in the average time spent on visit types "viewing" and "car configuration." This may be related to additional options or features added to the website, leading to more time spent on the site.

Take-2

  • As time passes, the number of sales and the revenue generated by sales increased.

  • This increase is mostly driven by the sales increase in the "Website" and "Mobile App" platforms. It's also worth noting that sales in "Dealership" have increased, but this increase is smaller compared to other platforms. Overall, the dealership is the platform that made the most sales, followed by the Mobile App and Website, respectively.

  • One of the most important takeaways is that these increases in different platforms also translate to revenue. At the beginning of 2020 Q3, the dealership was the most revenue-generating platform. However, by 2024 Q1, the Website platform took over, and it is now the most revenue-generating platform, even though it has the smallest number of sales.

  • However, over the entire time span, the "Dealership" platform remains the most revenue-generating platform, followed by the "Website" and the "Mobile App."

  • This might indicate that although the Website platform made the smallest number of sales, it is selling more expensive cars compared to other channels.

# Optimizing respect to Silhouette Score

In[]:
silhouette_scores = []
range_ = range(2, 105, 20)

for k in range_:
    gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=k)
    gmm.fit(df)
    labels = gmm.predict(df)
    score = silhouette_score(df, labels)
    silhouette_scores.append(score)

plt.plot(range_, silhouette_scores, marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of components')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.title('Silhouette Score for Gaussian Mixture Model')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
